A melting-pot of laid-back melodies, hip-hop rhythms and acoustic guitars, 
Shwayze&#039;s self-titled debut [Suretone/Geffen Records] pays homage to an 
all-day-and-into-the-night party lifestyle colored by the rolling tides of his 
hometown beaches, and the rolling papers that flavor the proceedings. 
Collaborating with Shwayze, Adler co-wrote all of the songs on the album, 
producing and providing backing vocals along the way.

The first single, "Buzzin&#039;" splashes Cisco&#039;s roots-rock acoustic-guitar and vocal 
tapestry with Shwayze&#039;s cooler-than-a-sea-breeze hip-hop delivery. Says the 
rapper, "It&#039;s a new West Coast sound, it&#039;s California chill, West Coast stoner 
music." Case in point? "Don&#039;t Be Shy." "It&#039;s about Malibu being like an endless 
summer. Cisco came up with the hook and the `da-don-don, da-don-don-
don&#039;t be shy&#039; part. I came up with the verses about a couple of chicks I was 
into. It&#039;s about wanting summer to come back, waiting for the sun and kicking 
it on the beach."
